      <div class="floated-media float-right">
          <img src="Snail.jpg" alt="Snail" />
          <p class="media-caption">Snails have been eaten for over a millenia throughout history. Archeologists date the earliest consumption of snails back to the early Gravettian era, roughly 30,000 years ago, after finding snail shells among the discarded animal remains in pits used for cooking food in the Gravettian era. Since this period, snails have gained large popularity, particularly rising to their fame as a delicacy in 1814 when Talleyrand (the 1st Prince of Benevento, French clergyman, politician and diplomat) wanted to impress the Tzar (emperor) of Russia, Alexander during his visit in Paris. Marie-Antoine Carême, an up and coming chef who owned his own restaurant, was instructed to prepare a dish Alexander had never tried before. The chef prepared a traditional “Escargots de Bourgogne” named after his hometown, Burgundy. The Tzar was incredibly impressed, so much so that he raved to everyone about the quality and deliciousness of the escargot. Popularity of escargot spread to the point of a near extinction of snails in burgundy in the 1970’s. A law was passed in 1979 prohibiting the harvesting of wild snails during the breeding season. Today many French restaurants receive their snails from Poland, Romania, Ukraine, or Hungary.</p>
      </div>

      <p>Snails are mollusks under the gastropoda class and although there are over 3000 breeds of snails, including herbivorous and carnivorous snails, many of them are not edible and can give you parasites such as rat lung worm or Angiostrongylus cantonensis. However, when the right breeds are prepared in the correct fashion, snails can be delicious and have numerous health benefits. Many may find snails to be particularly unpleasant to consume but, in many places around the world, snails are consumed as a highly healthy food source. Snails are made up of 80% water, 15% protein, and 2.4 percent fat on average and contain many nutrients such as vitamins (E, A, K, and B12), essential fatty acids (calcium, iron, selenium, and magnesium) and other helpful nutrients.</p>

      <div class="floated-media float-left">
          <img src="SnailMeat.jpg" alt="Snail Meat" />
          <p class="media-caption">Consumed as a delicacy in various dishes in many cultures, particularly in French and Mediterranean cuisine, snails are often prepared with garlic and butter sauce, but they can also be cooked in a variety of ways, including boiling, grilling, roasting, and baking. In addition to the meat of a snail, snail eggs are also consumed in some places as another sort of caviar. The meat of snails are commonly compared with the taste of fish or meat and the mouthfeel is similar to that of an oyster, the meat takes on the flavour profile of the ingredients you cook them with. Similar to caviar, snail eggs have a salty taste and are said to taste earthy and somewhat like mushrooms.</p>
      </div>

      <p>Snails are commonly enjoyed in places such as Andorra, Spain, France, Italy, Portugal (on the European side), Algeria, Morocco, and Tunisia (on the African side).</p>

      <p class="source-link">Tasty Photo Source: <a href="https://chateaubriand36.com/" target="_blank">Chateaubriand<sup>36</sup></a></p>

